One law, says Gladstone, yet remains 3 Though bars don't make a cage, or

Stone walls a gaol, the League in chains Is legalised vis major.

Then Leaguers cry, You banish laws, Or surely one might smash a

Thick head in this our holy cause Nor fear a lettre de cache-t.

In Ireland thus they all explain— And each with show of reason— How laws permit, and eke restrain,

Both loyalty and treason.
